Share Prices Marginally Higher on Singapore Market 
Share prices finished marginally higher on the Singapore market as the
benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index (STII) rose 6.81 points to
close at 1543.72 Monday.
Dealers said that the rise took place despite a sharp fall in property
stocks as regional currency markets remained largely stable.
Total market volume increased to 1,197.1 million units, valued at
1,061.998 million Singapore dollars (635.93 million U.S. dollars).
Declines overtook advances by 242 to 184, while 188 other counters
remained unchanged.
Renong Bhd was the most actively traded counter as it registered a
turnover of 88.68 million units. It was followed by Rekapac which had
65.1 million shares traded. MBf Capital was next with 55.22 million
shares changed hands.
Bukit Sembawang led the gainers of the day as it rose 90 cents to
finish at 9.8 Singapore dollars. C. Properties, the Singapore Press
Holdings (SPH), and Thai Prime Fund picked up 50 cents each to end at
11.5, 18.2 and 5.5 Singapore dollars respectively. Malaya Banking 200
was 45 cents higher at 5.85 Singapore dollars.
On the downside, City Developments, the Overseas Chinese Banking
Corporation (OCBC) Foreign, and the SPH Foreign shared the top spot on
the losers' list as each of them declined 50 cents to end at seven,
8.6, and 21.6 Singapore dollars respectively. Creative 50 and GP
Battery Warrant0011 fell 40 cents each to close at 33.1 and 1.48
Singapore dollars respectively.
